Women's basketball players did not reach the medal from the World Championship U17, finished fourth
The American women won their third World 17's Championship as well, beating Spain narrowly 77-75 in the final despite 40 points from Spain's Angela Salvadores.
"We really wanted to win and not be a potato, but maybe we wanted it too much. We caught the beginning but we couldn't hold on because they outplayed us under the basket," regretted captain Karolína Malečková. "But playing in front of such a crowd was an incredible experience," she praised the fans in Klatovy and Plzeň.
The Czechs started very well, taking an 8-0 lead thanks to two threes and dominating the court throughout the first quarter. At that point, it looked like they would avenge their 85:88 overtime defeat. However, the referees whistled 15 fouls in the half and with questionable decisions helped Hungary come back into the game with a 12:2 streak.
"I'm convinced that all we had to do was make two more three-pointers, run it to 20 points and we wouldn't have let it go. But instead, our mistakes came. I don't care about the referees, but what we did wrong, and there were mistakes that helped the opponent get caught," coach Richard Fousek assessed.
"It wasn't the first time we had a lapse in concentration. But the girls are fighters, they didn't let anything go and fought to the end. The opponent was very good," he added.
The Czechs were kept in the game mainly by Petra Holešínská's accurate shooting from distance and Tereza Šípová's peacock shot. However, the top Czech scorer had a problem with fouls and was absent from the court for a large part of the third quarter. The Hungarians took advantage of this and gained a slight lead, which they maintained, although the Czechs fought until the last seconds.
"The first five games were very difficult for us, we turned the games in a tight rotation and it cost us a lot of strength. Already against Spain we could see that the girls were tired and there was no place to take. We were not consistent on defense because of our physicality. We didn't play fast counterattack, we lacked rebounding. And the Hungarians are so good that if you don't put everything together, it's hard to win," Fousek added.
He believes his charges have a promising future. "In two years, the girls managed to win the Youth Olympics, be second at the 16-year-old European Championships and now they are fourth in the world. By our standards, this is a quality team with good character and we need to continue to work with them and develop their talent. Now it's up to the federation to decide which coach to assign them in the higher categories," added Fousek.
Thomas Cook: Czechs kicked out of hotel in Mallorca. The guarantees were not enough
The group's Austrian, German and Polish divisions also filed for insolvency during the week. The future of the Czech subsidiary is currently under negotiation, with a decision expected by the end of September.
According to Jan Papež, vice-chairman of the Association of Travel Agencies of the Czech Republic, there are three possible solutions in play - liquidation will be announced, the company will be sold or the team from the Czech branch will set up a new travel agency. "Which one it will be, however, cannot be predicted, it will depend on the German owner," he told the Czech News Agency today.
In addition to the two prematurely terminated tours, the CK is also dealing with cases where clients had to pay for their stay out of their own pocket, although the company tries to provide guarantees to hoteliers. The CK has promised to reimburse its clients for the payments, according to Pope, and the company has sufficient security to do so.
Problems in hotels have arisen especially in Mallorca, where the company has asked for help from the Czech consulate. In this context, Pope described to ČTK one of the cases when a hotel there kicked out all the tourists of the office. "The hotelier was unable to determine who belonged to the German and who to the Czech company. Therefore, he kicked everyone out of the hotel despite the fact that the domestic Neckermann provided guarantees," he said. According to Šrámek, the situation was eventually resolved.
The Czech arm of the bankrupt British Thomas Cook group increased its revenues to CZK 995 million last year, up nearly 21 percent year-on-year, according to the company's annual report. The company's net profit, on the other hand, fell by around CZK 7 million to CZK 15.3 million. However, the company was left with an outstanding loss of almost CZK 103 million from previous years. The subsidiary comprises two core divisions - in addition to CK Neckermann, it is also the Global Travel Lufthansa City Center business.
