Brno-based software development firm CCV is facing legal action from Finnish telecommunications equipment manufacturer Nokia. The Finns do not like the fact that the Brno firm's warehouse management software is called Lokia WMS, the E15 daily reported. Nokia has therefore filed objections against the Lokia trademark application with the Industrial Property Office. CCV believes that confusion is unlikely.
Marketing director Petr Ondrasek said that two dozen customers are already using the programme, which has been on the market since last September.
"The Nokia brand enjoys recognition and trust around the world. When someone tries to register a trademark that we believe may lead to confusion or dilution of our brand, we take action to protect our valuable asset," said Nokia spokesman Mark Durrant.
The Brno-based developers say they did not have the brand, famous in the past for its mobile phones, in mind when creating the stock programme. According to CCV, the name Lokia is based on the Latin name for a species of dragonfly whose rapid movement is meant to be analogous to the movement of warehouse workers through a warehouse.
"In the Czech market, the possibility of confusion is unlikely. We sell modern cloud software that companies use to equip their warehouse operations, and we are not really targeting the mobile phone manufacturing sector. And we don't want to be compared to a brand that may be missing the train in its field," CCV manager Tomáš Kormaňák told E15.
CCV applied for brand protection with the Industrial Property Office in August before the program was launched. "It applied for protection for goods and services belonging to classes 9, 35 and 42, as software belongs to class 9, related business management services in warehouses belong to class 35 and computer software development belongs to class 42 according to the international classification," Ondrášek said.
Nokia's opposition is based on the fact that Nokia's earlier trademark is valid in all classes of goods and services and thus covers the widest possible range of goods and services, and thus naturally overlaps also in classes 9, 35 and 42. "The CCV does not dispute the opponent's claim as far as the coincidence on these classes of products and services is concerned. However, in reality they are completely different marks aimed at different target groups," Ondrášek said.
According to E15, brand disputes can take months and can complicate a company's operations.
