Microplastics have reached human intestines, study confirms for the first time
Scientists have confirmed years of suspicions. A team led by Professor Philipp Schwabl of the University of Vienna has published a study that proves for the first time the presence of microplastics in human stool. The study is small, with eight participants from Europe, Japan and Russia - but tiny plastic particles measuring between 50 and 500 micrometres were found in the samples of all the people studied. None of the eight subjects were vegetarians, six avoided marine fish, and all drank water from plastic bottles and food packaged in plastic.
And it would actually be a bit of a miracle if nothing was found. We already know that microplastics - which are either produced directly, for example for the cosmetics industry, or created by the breakdown of larger pieces - are present in marine animals, insects, tap water and soda; in short, everywhere on the planet. So their entry into the human digestive tract is only officially confirmed. There were roughly 20 microplastic particles per ten grams of stool, and scientists estimate that more than half of the world's population will have them in them.
Of course, lay and scientific knowledge suspects that this is not good. But humanity still doesn't know how bad it is - and what effect microplastics have on "host" organisms. Small particles can reach the bloodstream or the lymphatic system and end up, for example, in the liver. "This is the first study of its kind and it confirms what we have long thought. Now that we have the first evidence of microplastics in the human body, we need to continue to investigate what exactly this means for human health," says Schwabl.
So far, it is known that microplastics in the gut can negatively affect the immune responses of the digestive system, thereby facilitating the absorption of toxic chemicals and other pathogens into the body. And so far, there is no known solution other than to reduce the use of plastics, especially polypropylene. But this will be difficult - the first task facing governments and authorities will be to at least halt its steep rise. As for plastic bottles alone, experts estimate that in three years' time humanity will be using a fifth more of them than today. The current rate is a staggering one million bottles bought per minute. Some eight million tonnes of plastic end up in the seas and oceans every year. The waste threatens marine ecosystems and contaminates the digestive systems of marine animals.
Some countries have already taken restrictions and other measures; Kenya, for example, has banned plastic bags under threat of draconian penalties. The European Commission is considering small bans (the well-known straws), and the domestic Ministry of the Environment is heading in the same direction. Critics, however, argue that such measures are nice, but totally inadequate.
Repair of the Krkonoše Museum will be delayed for a year
The administration of the Krkonoše National Park (KRNAP) has postponed by three weeks the deadline for submitting bids for the second tender for the repair of the Krkonoše Museum in Vrchlabí. The original deadline for opening the envelopes was 20 September, said Radek Drahný, spokesman for the national park. The reason for the postponement of the deadline for submitting bids is a reduction in the budget from CZK 110 million to CZK 83 million.
"We are currently working with prices that are on the market. There has been a change in the budget, it is the price we expect to be offered. If someone submits a bid that is acceptable, the work will start as soon as possible," Drahný said.
Compared to the original plans, the start of the museum's renovation is about a year late. KRNAP wanted to have a contractor selected for the construction part by the end of last year and to start work this spring. According to the national park administration, the CZK 123 million in European funding for the project is not in jeopardy.
The KRNAP administration has not been able to select a construction company for the museum repairs. It launched a second tender this summer because in the previous tender all the bids from companies significantly exceeded the then estimated price of CZK 65 million. The bids exceeded CZK 100 million.
The museum, which is housed in a former Augustinian monastery and belongs to the KRNAP Administration, has been closed since autumn 2017. The selected company should provide the construction part of the project. The total cost, including the construction of the new exhibition, is estimated at CZK 210 million. After the transformation of the expositions, a KRNAP visitor centre should be established in the now vacated building by the end of 2021.
The renovated museum with a new interactive exposition, which should be a story of nature and people settled in the mountains and build on the successful Stone and Life exposition, should serve as a representative gateway to the Krkonoše Mountains for visitors. The visitor centre should provide information about the past and present of the Giant Mountains in the most comprehensible way and motivate people to explore and protect the mountains. It should also take on the role of a traditional museum. The centre will also offer opportunities to organise concerts, festivals, theatre performances or lectures in the open air. There are plans to build a new entrance to the building, a research room or a café.
