"A scary result of the study." Islam does not belong in the West, overwhelming majority of Austrians think
1,200 respondents were surveyed, and the poll shows considerable distrust of Islam in Austrian society.
Almost 60 percent of Austrians fear that some Muslims are terrorists, and 48 percent would call for a ban on the construction of mosques. 80 percent of those polled are in favor of greater monitoring of Islamic centers.
A majority of Austrians also want Muslims to be restricted in their religious practices and say the presence of Muslims sometimes makes them feel like strangers in their own country.
"The result of the study is frightening," says study author Wolfgang Aschauer, adding: "Such a tendency towards ethnocentrism could lead over time to the adoption of discriminatory attitudes. The religious freedoms granted to Muslims are in danger of being curtailed."
For believers, the critical attitude is less pronounced. Aschauer argues that the conflict in Austria is not between religions, but between cultures. Dialogue and education could help blunt polarisation, the sociologist says.
According to the study, the most hostile attitudes towards Muslims are held by voters of the extreme right, people without a university education and seniors over 75. On the other hand, Green Party voters, people under 30 and university graduates are the most supportive.
The Austrian Ministry of the Interior estimates that there are around 700 000 Muslims in Austria, which has a population of around 8.7 million. The vast majority have Turkish roots. There are more than 400 Muslim prayer houses and mosques in the country and Islam has been officially recognised as a religion since 1912.
Which cities will disappear under the sea?
A vote by the upper house of the Canadian Parliament has confirmed a rumour that has been known for days: Canada is revoking the honorary citizenship of former human rights legend and Nobel Peace Prize laureate Daw Aung San Suu Kyi. The current leader of Myanmar (Burma), who spent years under house arrest for her efforts to bring freedom to her country, has lost her honorary title because of her involvement in the genocide against the minority Rohingya people.
The decision to strip Suu Kyi of her honorary citizenship was approved by the lower legislature a week ago and senators have now unanimously backed it. "This is the right message for her, for Myanmar and for the whole world," commented independent Senator Ratna Omidvar on her colleagues' decision. "We must make it clear that accomplices to genocide are not welcome here in Canada - even less so as honorary citizens."
The Canadian Parliament's verdict does not technically change anything for Suu Kyi, it is just an honorary title, but on a symbolic level it sends a strong message. The silence of a long-time human rights activist on the atrocities that the military in majority-Buddhist Myanmar has been committing for endless months against the Rohingya Muslim minority is intolerable.
The fact that officially organised genocide is taking place in Myanmar and that Suu Kyi - the de facto Prime Minister of that government - has utterly failed in her duty to protect her citizens was recently brought to light by a UN report. Specifically, it mentions the names of several army commanders who, according to the investigation team, should be brought to justice for crimes against humanity committed in actions which, the report says, 'are shocking both in the horror of their acts and in their sheer scale'. Suu Kyi and the administration she led, the UN said, were complicit primarily by covering up the soldiers' actions and releasing a protective fog of lies around them - for example, that it was an "anti-terrorist operation".
With Suu Kyi's removal, five individuals remain on Canada's list of honorary citizens: the Swedish diplomat Raoul Wallenberg, Nelson Mandela, Tenzin Gyatso, the 14th Dalai Lama, Karim Aga Khan IV, the 49th Imam of Shiite Muslims, and Malala Yousufzai.
Developments around the former icon of the struggle for freedom and democracy have also been reflected in the Canadian Museum of Human Rights, where Suu Kyi's profile has been updated to include information on atrocities against the Rohingya and the parliamentary decision to strip her of her honorary citizenship. "We have also dimmed the light on her photo on a board depicting the timeline of the human rights struggle and are thinking of replacing her face with a portrait of a member of the Rohingya minority," Canadian media quoted museum spokesperson Rorie McLeod as saying.
Thus, in the current upheaval, the only thing that remains for Suu Kyi - at least for now - is the Nobel Peace Prize, awarded to her in 1991 at the suggestion of Václav Havel for her enormous contribution to the struggle for democracy. "While Ms Suu Kyi's current actions are regrettable, her award will not be annulled," Nobel Foundation head Lars Heikensten told Canada's CBS.
