Technology companies want to rule our cities
Francis Fukuyama has been somewhat burned by history. In 1992, at the height of the wave of liberalism that followed the end of the Cold War and the fall of the Iron Curtain, this political scientist wrote in his most famous book, The End of History and the Last Man: "What we may be witnessing ... is the final point in the ideological evolution of humanity and the universal acceptance of Western liberal democracy as the final form of government."
Twenty-six years later, we are witnessing rather illiberal models triumphing and various forms of nationalism and radicalism thriving from the US to Russia, from Turkey to Poland, and from Hungary to Italy. Fukuyama's current ninth book, Identity: The Demand for Dignity and the Politics of Resentment, attempts to counter these forces. As his interview by George Eaton for the New Statesman shows, he rethinks many of his former positions: he argues that the ideas of socialism should be brought back into the public sphere, and Marx was right in many ways. Though he also insists that his thought is still in line with the position of the 1990s and that critics of The End of History and The Last Man have misunderstood him.
"What I said even then was that one of the problems with modern democracy is that while it provides peace and prosperity, people want more than that... Liberal democracy doesn't even try to define what the good life is. It leaves that up to individuals who feel alienated, who don't see the point, and so they band together in identity-based groups that give them a sense of belonging."
In its day, The End of History and the Last Man was written as a powerful argument against Marxists who saw communism as the final stage of history. When Fukuyama is asked about how he now sees the rise of socialists in Britain and the US, he replies: "It all depends on what you mean by socialism. If we're talking about ownership of the means of production, then except when clear public services are demanded, I don't think it will work. But if you mean redistributive programs that attempt to address the huge income and wealth imbalances we are seeing, then yes. I think not only could it come back, it should come back. The long period that President Reagan and Prime Minister Thatcher started, in which certain types of ideas about the benefits of an unregulated market came into play, had a disastrous effect in many ways."
Finally, Fukuyama attempts to calm the current situation as well, warning all liberals that even the rise of new not-quite-democratic regimes will not be the end of history.
Civilization on borrowed time
I was recently reminded of a lovely "line" from one of the great short stories by Simek and Grossmann, set partly in a cemetery, which goes like this: "I pointed out to her that she was crying all right, but on someone else's grave!" It occurred to me that many of the world's politicians engaged in the senseless fight against climate change are now behaving very similarly.
They behave as if humans ruled planet Earth. In reality, we are but a speck on its surface, which it can blow away with its enormous forces like a gust of wind blowing out a candle flame. Probably few of them watch the famous British and American science documentaries about the destructive powers of our blue marble. After all, all it would take is for one of the larger active volcanoes to get a good "fart" and our advanced civilization would go down in flames.
And that this will happen in the near future is highly likely. A number of large volcanoes have, in the opinion of leading volcanologists, become "charged and armed" (Katla in Iceland, for example).
In a way, it would be ideal if the eruption, if it must happen one day, were to happen as soon as possible. Before trillions of dollars are wasted on measures to reduce the production of carbon dioxide, because any properly angry volcano, together with dust and poisonous volcanic gases, can release at least a hundred times more of it into the air than has been saved at the expense of the people of Europe.
It therefore makes no sense to forcibly limit CO2 production. Moreover, it has been scientifically proven that, with a significantly higher proportion of CO2 in the air, plants produce more biological matter and are also more resistant to drought. For humanity, any warming is much more favourable than, for example, a rapid return of the ice age.
If we take into account the as yet understudied influence of solar cycles on the Earth's climate, we have only one reasonable conclusion: let us try hard to keep the Earth as clean as possible, and let us try to adapt to other changes with which we cannot compare in strength at the lowest possible cost.
