Deliberate slander? Ústí Zoo is looking for a new vet, no one is interested
The last time was at the end of this month. The city management attributes it to the rumours that emerged around the former zoo director and veterinarian Václav Poživil that he purposely killed the exotic animals in his care. For example, the female rhinoceros Zamba, the elephant Kala or the orangutan Ňuňák.
The city council has therefore issued a new contract. "For veterinary care for the zoo with an estimated value of performance of CZK 3.5 million excluding VAT and for the city's Centre for Animals in Need with an estimated value of performance of CZK 2.8 million excluding VAT," said city spokesperson Romana Macová.
Deputy Mayor Věra Nechybová (UFO) explained that this is the third time the city has announced a competition for veterinary services. "Dr Poživil had to explain the unfounded suspicions. I consider it an outrageous dishonesty of such a high-quality professional," she noted.
She said there are very few experts specialising in exotic animals. "It's certainly not a nice thing to do. Meanwhile, the zoo is providing veterinary care through orders," she said. Orders and contract cost the same money. "But the zoo has to comply with the law on public procurement as far as financing is concerned," zoo spokeswoman Nikola Roštejnská explained.
Václav Poživil himself is a respected expert. For example, he took part in a unique operation in which the cheetah Jane from Ústí nad Labem received the world's first total endoprosthesis. He served as the zoo's director from 2009 to 2012. He has not commented on the anonymous defamation of his person. He did not take phone calls or respond to text messages yesterday.
As for the zoo contract, some zookeepers believe that the zero interest in it may not necessarily be due to fears of such purposeful accusations as in his case, but simply a lack of awareness. For example, Jiří Král, a veterinarian in Ústí nad Labem, has not heard of it yet. "This is the first time I have heard it from you. No one has approached us. I think this kind of thing will spread quickly," he said.
