The couple wrapped the bitch in tape and drowned her in the river, the children found the bag
The case took place at the end of July in a village around Valašské Klobouk. A 27-year-old woman brought home a donated dog, aged one to two years, which she wanted to take care of. However, her partner, who was ten years older, did not like the fact that it was a bitch, so he decided to get rid of it.
"He wrapped the animal with duct tape and rope and greatly eliminated its vocal expression. He placed the dog in a jute bag, which he tied up. Then they drove the animal together to the river, where they dumped it in the bag. At the moment when the dog was thrown into the water, the dog was demonstrably alive," said Zlín police spokeswoman Monika Kozumplíková.
The following day, children playing by the river found the jute bag on the bank. When they opened it, they discovered the body of a dead dog inside. They called out to a woman who was passing by and ran away. The woman reported the incident to the police emergency line 158.
"Thanks to the knowledge of the town's residents, the police have identified the likely perpetrator of this incredible act. And they weren't wrong. Both the man and the woman confessed to the crime and described how the incident took place," the police spokeswoman added.
An expert opinion from the field of veterinary medicine confirmed that the dog died in an unequivocally agonizing manner as a result of suffocation, with the animal suffering for several minutes before dying.
"The actions of the perpetrators undoubtedly show a clear intention to get rid of the animal at any cost in this despicable way, even though they could have donated or sold the dog. The criminal police commissioner from Zlín charged the pair with the crime of animal cruelty committed in complicity. If convicted, the two accused could spend up to three years behind bars," Kozumplíková said.
Declaration of the end of the right in the lower house or What kind of "right-wing" coalition of ODS, TOP 09, STAN and KDU?
Recently, media and commentaries have been reporting on the upcoming coalition of the aforementioned parties. Many are applauding the fact that the "right" is finally getting its act together, but I rather wonder why these parties still call themselves right-wing.
Leaving aside the new Trikolora movement, the Czech Chamber of Deputies no longer has a real right-wing party. And it doesn't matter what the entities call themselves or what labels the mainstream media parrot. ODS is hardly centrist in its average of top politicians of this party, TOP 09 is clearly a party of the urban pseudo-liberal left (which is ashamed of its leftism and so hypocritically labels itself as conservative or even right-wing). STAN is a party that in its conception, ideology and electoral targeting is basically merged with TOP 09 (the reason for its existence is simply not clear to me). And the KDU even labels itself as centrist for a long time - but their political compass is much more to the left than they say.
Do you feel I've taken everyone out of the same water? No, I'm basing it on the actual policy actions of these parties. If I consider myself to be a classically liberal right-wing voter, my highest value is individual liberty, the free market and minimal government interference in the lives of individuals and the economy. How do these parties fulfil this general assumption of right-wingness? How many laws chopping away at people's freedoms in a salami-slicing fashion, raising taxes, endorsing new regulations and increasing surveillance, increasing ties to the socialist EU, or promoting environmental and gender madness have they supported in recent years? A lot, really a lot. Not their own labels, but actions identify them. These parties, despite all sorts of declarations or partial concessions, want to strengthen the role of the state in our lives. And that has nothing to do with right-wingism.
I would not be surprised at all by the coalition cooperation of TOP 09, STAN and KDU, they simply belong together on the political map and, apart from the Christian or, on the contrary, homosexual and gender aspects, I do not see any obvious difference for voters in terms of the influence of the state on their lives. However, the ODS has long portrayed itself as "the only right-wing party" and by associating itself with these three entities it is already revealing its true political alignment in a disingenuous way.
By the way, since I briefly mentioned the labels. Have you noticed how often all these parties quite uniformly and cheaply label critics of the dirigisme and socialism coming from the European Union as pro-Russian agents? Can they not or just do not want to understand that there are many people who do not like Euro-socialism and growing unfreedom as much as they do the authoritarian regime in Russia? Are they not hiding their utter argumentative incompetence and their gratuitous or blind adoration of the EU?
In short, it is possible that in the Czech Republic politics other than centrist politics no longer has a chance of greater success. Perhaps this is the kind of association the voters really want. Perhaps they want left-of-centre politics under the guise of 'right' because they are ashamed of their political convictions (or cannot even identify them). I don't know. But I am certainly not one of those voters.
