Terrorism is the main enemy against which all countries of the world should fight together. Czech Prime Minister Andrej Babiš said this today at the end of a five-day visit to the United States at the New York memorial to the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks. On this occasion, the Prime Minister paid tribute to the memory of two victims of Czech origin.
"This is a very moving place," the Prime Minister said as he, accompanied by his wife Monika, laid a white rose at the names of Lukáš Rambousek and Czechoslovak emigrant Alena Sešínová. The two were among the more than 2,750 people killed in the attack by hijacked planes on the former twin skyscrapers of the World Trade Center (WTC). The WTC towers collapsed after the impact, and a memorial with a list of names of the victims now stands in their place.
"We need to remember what happened here, the horror," Babiš said. The prime minister described the September 11, 2001 attack on the United States as a reason why the UN should work together in a united campaign against international terrorism. In addition to destroying the WTC skyscrapers, the terrorists then crashed a hijacked plane into the Department of Defense building in Washington and planned another strike on a target in Washington, presumably the White House or Congress. But this plane crashed when the passengers confronted the hijackers.
"This is our main enemy, this is where all the countries of the world should unite and fight international terrorism in a coordinated way," the Czech prime minister said.
