Undated image shows Adolf Hitler visiting Czechoslovak border fortifications. The role of the forts was never to stop the German army, but to slow its advance before the Allies became involved.
If, almost exactly 81 years ago, Czechoslovakia had rejected the Munich Agreement and subsequently faced a German attack, what would have taken the most Czechoslovak soldiers out of the fight? German tanks, air force, or perhaps artillery? Quite possibly it would have been none of these weapons, even though the Germans had overwhelming superiority over the Czechoslovaks in them. The Czechoslovak army would probably have suffered the greatest losses - because of the blisters.
In Nantes, a man confessed to the cathedral fire.
The Cathedral of Saints Peter and Paul in the heart of Nantes caught fire last Saturday, and the fire severely damaged the original 16th century stained glass windows and destroyed the organ.
The suspected arson was being investigated by investigators due to the fact that the fire progressed through the cathedral from three different locations.
At the same time, police found no signs at the entrances that anyone had forced their way into the cathedral.
The accused is a volunteer with the local diocese, a thirty-nine-year-old Rwandan refugee.
Police arrested him shortly after the fire but then released him without prosecuting him.
Now the prosecutor's office has reported that based on new evidence, the man was re-arrested on Saturday, confessed and faces charges of arson.
If found guilty, he faces up to ten years in prison and a hefty fine.
According to his lawyer, the man regrets the crime and has decided to cooperate fully with investigators, Le Monde reported.
Zeman the monument keeper - Man straining constitution calls for law enforcement
Those who live in a camp-divided society and don't want to go completely mad will welcome situations where they don't have to root only for their own. When he can also give credit to those he otherwise criticizes. If only so that he does not feel that he is oriented only according to pre-assigned labels. Such situations include the list of badly damaged monuments that President Zeman uses during his favourite trips to the regions.
Everyone knows what it is. And anyone who occasionally wanders through the Czech Republic sees many of these devastated monuments - from the centres of historic towns to individual castles, monasteries, old houses, churches and estates - with their own eyes. Everyone suspects that demagoguery can come into play here too. That if we accuse the town hall of not caring for monuments or some horror in the zoning plan, it may be the work of former administrations. Or a privatised building whose owner is untraceable. The head of state challenges local politicians: "A section of the Landmarks Act allows you to fine owners of buildings who don't take care of their property." But even if the owner is untraceable, it must be admitted that the president is calling for law enforcement. Which even critics of his Constitution-bending should acknowledge as a plus.
Of course, Miloš Zeman would not be Miloš Zeman if he considered all the details and formalities of a complex issue. But he is standing up for a good cause, much like the squatters he himself does not recognize. Two years ago, we wrote: "For all the name-calling, the squatters draw attention to an issue that stands outside the current concern. That this or that building is in a state of disrepair." And let's face it, the president is de facto doing the same thing.
If you come to the historic centre of Jáchymov, you are amazed at how devastated it is - including the houses with Renaissance cores. At a time when Jáchymov is celebrating 500 years of silver mining and the minting of thalers (dollars to Americans). Why? Because of a quick-fire sale of houses in the 1990s, local officials say. But why is it that Ostrov, seven kilometres away, the seat of the Šlik family who minted the Jáchymov thalers, has its historic core nicely repaired? It is good if the president draws attention to these things.
Vojtěch: On Monday we will introduce a "traffic light" for epidemiological measures
The new system is supposed to act as a pandemic plan, for the absence of which the government and the Ministry of Health are facing criticism.
"The grades will be according to the strength of the community spread," the minister explained.
He added that currently, for example, the Moravian-Silesian region or Prague would reach the medium, orange level.
The system is designed to be regional because the situation varies significantly from region to region, he added.
The ministry worked with epidemiologists and the Institute of Health Information and Statistics (IHIS) on the system.
The minister said specific measures would be linked to the different levels, whether it was the obligation to wear masks or the organisation of special wards in hospitals.
Interior Minister Jan Hamáček (ČSSD) called for the creation of an epidemiological plan on the Prima Partie television programme, saying that people should have clear information on what measures they can expect if the epidemiological situation worsens.
The daily increase in confirmed cases in the Czech Republic has been rising in recent days, although the number of people hospitalised remains low.
Vojtěch commented that nothing major is happening and it is not appropriate to talk about declaring a state of emergency or reconvening the crisis staff.
In view of the rising number of infected people, the government has reintroduced the obligation to wear masks at indoor events of over 100 people since Saturday across the country.
From Monday, the capacity of such events will be limited to 500 people, currently at 1,000.
The government's action, which did not make it clear until the last minute what measures would take effect or when they would be announced, has been criticised.
"I think that in a situation that is quite tense, the main actors should create a sense of certainty and, on the contrary, straighten out the confusion," Senator Marek Hilšer said in his Questions.
The measures may already vary by region, for example, in Prague from Sunday the obligation to wear masks also applies in non-residential medical facilities, i.e. in pharmacies or in waiting rooms at the doctor's office.
Since Friday, the obligation to wear balaclavas when visiting health and social care facilities and pharmacies has also been introduced in the Liberec and Ústí regions.
In the Vysočina region of Jihlava, it has been compulsory to wear balaclavas in indoor public areas, public transport and health facilities since 14 July.
On the other hand, in the Moravian-Silesian Region, anti-epidemic measures have been relaxed, as well as in the Central Bohemian Region in Kutná Hora.
In early June, the Czech government also approved the so-called traffic light for Europe, which differentiates the level of risk of infection in individual European countries by colour and adjusts the rules for entry into the Czech Republic from these countries accordingly.
For low- and medium-risk countries, the authorities have not required Czech citizens to have a negative coronavirus test or ordered quarantine instead since 15 June.
These are compulsory when Czechs return from high-risk countries.
At the moment, all EU member states are now in the low-risk category.
Costa Rica is a champion in the fight against climate change
Costa Rica received the title for several reasons. For starters, for its plan to be carbon neutral by 2050 - something many countries have committed to under the Paris Agreement. The Central American nation, with a population of around five million, produces only 0.4 percent of the world's emissions. Costa Rica has also pledged to switch fully to renewable energy by 2030, with 70 percent of its buses or taxis running on electricity.
The official tourism organization says that roughly 95 percent of its energy already comes from renewable sources - in 2017, Costa Rica ran on them for a total of 300 days.
Costa Rica boasts nearly 30 national parks.
The density of forestation also contributes to reduced emissions. The rainforests with their diverse flora and fauna, which cover more than half of the country, are also one of the main tourist draws. "Costa Rica is a pioneer in conservation and sets an example for other countries in the region, as well as around the world. Climate change requires urgent action from all of us," the UN said in a statement.
Costa Rica boasts nearly 30 national parks, which is a lot considering the country's small size (51,100 square kilometers). Rain or mist forests, coral reefs or mangrove swamps are home to five percent of the world's biodiversity. The country also has volcanoes, pitoreal waterfalls and you would also find several rescue stations for sloths.
