Thank you for the dance! Singer Leonard Cohen's final album to be released posthumously
The album Thank You for the Dance will include unreleased material and various musical collaborations put together by the singer's son. The album will be released on November 22.
In October 2016, You Want it Darker, an album Cohen collaborated on with his son Adam, was released. He asked him to help him finish each song. On the intimate recording, Cohen symbolically comes to terms with his impending death. He died a month after the album's release at the age of 82.
Seven months later, Adam Cohen began working on the material left over from his father. He brought in a number of musicians to collaborate with him - Damien Rice, Bryce Dessner, Javier Mas and singer Beck, to name a few.
"When we came up with the music for my father's words, we used his own distinctive musical techniques. So he's still with us," Adam Cohen said of the album. "What impresses me most about it is the reaction of those who have heard it. One by one they say Leonard is still alive," he added.
The album's first swallow is the short song The Goal. "I'm almost alive, I'm almost home," Cohen sings in his trademark honeyed voice. He was singing about death, sensing he wouldn't live to see the release of the new material. He admitted as much in an interview with The New Yorker magazine a month before his death. "I'm ready to die. I hope it won't be too unpleasant," he said.
In September 2018, Adam Cohen released a collection of his father's poetry called The Flame. It will be published in English as The Flame on December 31 by Argo.
