The convenience of paying by card can be appreciated by travellers in almost all parts of the world. This is especially true in popular tourist destinations, but today credit cards are accepted almost everywhere. "People who travel more frequently, for example for work, don't have time to go to exchange offices repeatedly to exchange cash. And even 'holiday makers' don't want to rely on cash to make ends meet. Moreover, some foreign currencies are not even available in Czech banks or exchange offices. Therefore, we have solved this with the NEO account so that its users can withdraw cash from all ATMs, wherever they are, free of charge," says Kateřina Petko, Marketing and Communications Director and Spokesperson of Expobank CZ.
Moreover, a payment card is a much more reliable way to avoid losing your money than cash. If a full wallet is lost, its owner may never see the money he or she was carrying in it again. However, if he loses only his payment card, he can easily block it instantly by phone or through online banking. By acting quickly, he may not suffer any financial loss at all. "Keeping money in a bank account has other advantages besides its reliable protection. In the case of the NEO account, for example, the interest rate of 1.6% per annum is one of the highest among current and savings accounts. It is set up and managed completely online without the need to visit a branch. In addition, the money in the bank account is insured up to EUR 100,000 and the maintenance of the account is completely free," adds Kateřina Petko.
Travel insurance should be a matter of course for anyone who is going abroad. Thanks to the possibility of arranging it and paying by card online, this can be done even at the last minute. However, the mere possession of a credit card often means insurance protection when travelling. "For example, with the embossed MasterCard Gold and MasterCard Business cards, travel insurance is an integral part of foreign travel to all countries around the world. Holders of these cards can also insure the family they are travelling with. This often eliminates the need for any additional arrangements," adds Kateřina Petko from Expobank CZ. However, it is always advisable to check the scope of the insurance, i.e. whether it covers all the activities that the travellers plan to undertake.
The Ministry plans to introduce a flat-rate meal allowance from 2021.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing an amendment to the Income Tax Act, according to which the employee would receive money for meals directly. According to the Ministry of Finance, a quarter of employees, i.e. about one million people who do not receive meal vouchers yet, will be eligible for food support.
However, according to David Rýc, chairman of the Association of Voucher System Operators, many small companies that do not have a canteen or meal vouchers provide their employees with meals, for example by importing food or by making agreements with restaurants.
"The essence of the intention is that we do not change anything about the tax advantage. Furthermore, it will not be used to pay health and social insurance," Schiller said on Friday. She added that the limit for the maximum employer contribution applicable as a tax credit would also remain.
