Bloomberg: Venezuela has hidden bitcoins and doesn't know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank is conducting internal tests to see if it can hold cryptocurrencies. It's responding to a directive from state-owned Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which is seeking to be able to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank and then have the bank pay the oil firm's suppliers in cryptocurrencies. The staff is also studying a proposal to allow the central bank to count cryptocurrencies against foreign exchange reserves, which are now near a 30-year low. Citing information from four sources, Bloomberg reported.
Sanctions imposed by the United States on President Nicolás Maduro's authoritarian regime have largely cut Venezuela off from the global financial system. This has exacerbated the economic crisis in the country. Meanwhile, the current crisis is one of the most serious in global comparison, which has forced officials to use a mixture of different methods to move money around. While Maduro's efforts to launch the world's first state-owned cryptocurrency have failed, the ongoing efforts to use digital currencies show how desperate the government is to find ways around the restrictions.
Neither the Venezuelan central bank nor PDVSA responded to a request for comment.
It is not clear how PDVSA came to own bitcoins and ether, nor how much value it holds in these currencies. The company has struggled to get payments from customers through conventional channels because large banks are unwilling to do business with sanctioned entities. Last month, the company received most of a $700 million (16.6 billion) payment in Chinese yuan because the parties were unable to find financial institutions to facilitate the transaction.
PDVSA may be reluctant to sell cryptocurrencies on the open market because it would require it to register with the exchange and undergo due diligence, so-called due diligence. Instead, it wants the cryptocurrency to be used by the central bank to pay the entities to which PDVSA owes money. Oil company officials believe that the central bank is less exposed to potential obstacles that could arise when paying with cryptocurrency.
Bitcoins and ethers use a decentralized internet ledger known as a blockchain to verify and record transactions. In some cases, relatively anonymous transfers are enabled without the need for an intermediary. Few banks are engaging in digital currencies because of the money laundering and customer information issues that come with them and complicate compliance.
Cryptocurrencies are experiencing a comeback this year after the debacle of 2018 due to expectations of greater adoption by institutions and Facebook's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. Even so, they remain volatile. Bitcoin is down nearly 20 percent in the last four days, but has gained about 130 percent since the beginning of the year.
Jan Sindelar's comment: Run the railways like a business
Sky's election, while apparently not entirely smooth, is the culmination of a sad tale of the state's inability to give the railways clear direction. The board has been incomplete for over a year and even after Wednesday night that hasn't changed, as one of the members has resigned. The standstill continues.
The selection process itself was a farce from the start, if only because the requirements for candidates, especially in terms of experience, were significantly relaxed. Compared to last year's selection, the requirements for the size of the company in which the candidate had worked in the past were reduced. First the members of the selection committee and then the supervisory board played only the role of pimps.
Nebeský submitted probably the weakest professional CV of the five finalists, yet without experience from a large company he beat out experienced fighters from the management of logistics giants and transport companies. It was the participation of interesting managers from the private sector that was probably the brightest aspect (and the best hope) of the whole process. Today, those involved know that they played only the role of stage sets in a political game.
Perhaps Nebeský will surprise, show great talent and eventually emerge as the best rail boss ever. At least in the beginning, however, he will be accompanied by the aftertaste of political embarrassment. The Czech Railways will not face an easy period, they have to cope with competition in the liberalisation of the market and with a shortage of staff in operations. There is a shortage of drivers, shunters and mechanics. How can they be motivated to continue working and respect the management if the state behaves like an elephant in the china shop in the top management?
The second important group is the creditors. We will see how they interpret the games at the top of the railways next spring when the railways defend their rating. What is certain is that creditors perceive instability. The sad thing is that someone else goes to Moody's every year to defend the rating on behalf of ČD. The agency has not escaped the frequent changes in the management of ČD and the political influence on the company, and has criticised them already this summer.
The ANO movement advocates, among other things, that the state should be run like a company. For a start, it would be enough if one large state-owned company were run like a company and not like a state. Czech Railways is still one of the largest companies in the country and it would be good if it were run by the best. They have applied, but the state has snubbed them. It can certainly be argued that the post of head of the railways has always been a political matter. But then we can forgive the antics of the selection process.
An unusually open and unique image of Karel Gott in Olga Špátová's feature-length documentary
This unique film from the work of Olga Špátová will premiere in Czech cinemas next spring.
"In mid-September last year, Ivanka and Karel Gott called me and asked me if I would make a documentary about his life with Karel again after ten years. I didn't hesitate a minute! It was and is a great honour for me to film with a man who endured more than half a century in the limelight of Czech culture thanks to his exceptional singing talent, artistic humility and immeasurable diligence. I accepted the challenge to make a feature-length documentary about Karel Gott, whose art has brought joy to three generations of listeners, as a commitment to this legendary singer," says director Olga Špátová.
The first day of filming took place on 22 October last year thanks to a quick arrangement and agreement, and the last shots with Karel Gotts were filmed a few days ago. The goal was and is absolutely clear - to capture authentically Karel Gott as a phenomenal singer who gives himself away to his fans, as a painter, but also as a loving husband and father of his children. A man who for sixty years has been giving joy to several generations with his songs, not only in this country, but also in Europe, and indeed all over the world. A man who has etched himself into the hearts and souls of his listeners by simply being.
The film is not meant to be a showcase of Karel Gott's undisputed fame and achievements. "That's why it's not even possible to compare my previous film, The Gott Phenomenon, with this current one. Each is different. At least in the fact that we filmed them at a different stage in Karel Gott's life, and this is very evident in the personal, almost intimate confession he gave us, which confirmed to all of us what a legend we have the opportunity to work with and spend time with, which is truly indescribable," adds Olga Špátová.
The filmmakers captured Karel Gott during his performances, during meetings with his fans in our country and in Hamburg, but especially in his home environment, whether in Prague, at his cottage in Czech Switzerland, in the village where he spent his childhood, and in other places that played an important role in his life. Thanks to Karel Gott's frank openness, the film will be completely authentic and unique.
"Olga has a great gift for filming with her close-knit team, so that we often let ourselves get carried away by the spontaneous atmosphere and naturally let her into our private lives, which allowed me to talk about quite intimate topics. With my husband, cinematographer Jan Malíř, they actually became part of our family. We originally wanted to release the film in 2019, when I celebrated my anniversary. But since I still had a wonderful summer with my family, I wanted us to film for as long as possible. Well, and since I was all over the place in 2019, my wish was to have it released in theaters next spring. This documentary is a thank you to my fans and everyone who has supported and accompanied me in my profession," says Karel Gott himself about the film.
