Managers of state-owned companies are to go through a new selection process. Law will be circumvented, opposition claims
"This is a typical bill that is unnecessary," said Zbyněk Stanjura, chairman of the ODS parliamentary club.
After several unsuccessful attempts, the Chamber of Deputies has approved changes to prevent the future opaque distribution of functions - critics talk of "trafics" - in state-owned companies. Candidates would now have to go through a selection process at the relevant ministry and will also be considered by the government's personnel nominations committee.
However, this is a compromise solution, which ODS, for example, does not like because it will allegedly allow ministers to make excuses that the selection committees are responsible for any poor selection of state managers. Moreover, the opinion of the committee will not be binding on the minister. The amendment still needs to be approved by the Senate and signed by President Miloš Zeman.
