Police charged CzechTourism manager Ales Pangrac over promotion contracts
Police have charged former CzechTourism manager Ales Pangrac over promotion contracts. Pangrác confirmed to SeznamZprávy that he accepted the charges this week. Czech Television (ČT) reported last year that police officers were investigating contracts worth CZK 38 million in the case. Police said some of the money was going back to Pangrác, the server said. In the case, detectives were also interested in Regional Development Minister Klára Dostálová (ANO), under whose ministry CzechTourism falls. According to the server, the investigation into the case is still ongoing.
Detectives from the National Centre against Organised Crime secured evidence in the case in the second half of last November. They have been to the headquarters of the CzechTourism, the Czech Ministry for Regional Development, the Most Autodrom and the Sport Invest agency. They also took a service computer from the minister's apartment. The court order for the search of Dostalová's home, which was previously quoted by ČT, stated that in 2016, when she was deputy minister, the minister made decisions about CzechTourism's spending in favour of selected persons indirectly and outside of standard official procedure. At the time, Dostálová said she felt absolutely innocent, she had not made any mistakes, she could document everything and she was cooperating fully with the police.
According to the agency, this was misconduct by an individual. The media had previously reported that the former director of the Regional Partnership Department at CzechTourism, Ales Pangrac, had been dismissed because of the audit results. It showed that CzechTourism had concluded 48 problematic contracts.
"Yes, they accused me. But I don't want to comment any further," Pangrác told Seznam Zprávy North.
