Shops destroyed, fires in the streets, riots accompanied the memorial parade
Five years ago, 43 Ayotzinapa college students went missing, despite extensive investigations, the case has not been solved. The students were allegedly detained by police in the Mexican state of Guerrero. It is unclear exactly what happened afterwards, but investigations suggest that the students apparently ended up in the hands of a local syndicate and were subsequently killed and burned, APTN reports.
A memorial parade was held in the Mexican capital on Thursday as families sought to express their frustration at the continuing failure to find answers and explain their children's disappearance.
But the mostly peaceful march was disrupted by small groups of vandals who destroyed everything in their path. Vandals destroyed shops and hotels, vandalised monuments, set fires and broke windows around the city.
Even before the march, President Andres Manuel López Obrador said he would do everything possible to catch them and asked the public for any information that would lead to clarification of the case.
More than 142 people have been arrested as part of the investigation, but not one of them has been convicted. Many of them had to be released because their human rights were violated, with investigators allegedly torturing suspects, APTN added.
Putin telephones Zelensky ahead of Donbass ceasefire, Kremlin criticises planned elections
Russian President Vladimir Putin spoke by phone with his Ukrainian counterpart Volodymyr Zelensky about the situation in Donbass, where a new ceasefire is due to take effect from midnight.
According to a Kremlin statement, Putin criticised, among other things, the Ukrainian parliament's decision to hold local elections; Kiev reported that Zelensky called for the release of detained Ukrainians.
The new ceasefire was agreed on Wednesday evening by negotiators from Ukraine and Russia, backed by the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
The ceasefire is due to begin after midnight on Monday night, is to be "complete and universal" and is intended to open the way for the implementation of other provisions of the peace accords.
In the interview, Putin told Zelensky that the Ukrainian parliament's decision to hold local elections contradicts the Minsk peace agreement and threatens the prospects for a settlement of the conflict in eastern Ukraine.
Ukraine's parliament decided last week that upcoming local elections would not be held in territories controlled by pro-Russian rebels.
The Minsk agreement stipulates that Kiev will regain control of the border of Ukrainian territories occupied by separatists with Russia after granting these regions broad autonomy and holding local elections there.
According to Unian, Zelensky's office said the two statesmen agreed on the usefulness of the upcoming ceasefire in Donbas as well as the need to implement other measures to promote peace in the region, such as demining areas of fighting or withdrawing some troops from the frontline.
Zelensky also called on Putin to release Ukrainians detained in eastern Ukraine, the occupied Crimea peninsula and in Russia itself.
The Minsk agreement has helped stop the fighting, but people continue to die on both sides of the front in sporadic gun battles and artillery attacks.
The conflict in Donbas has claimed over 14,000 lives since the spring of 2014.
Ukraine and the West accuse Russia of militarily supporting the separatists, a charge Moscow denies.
Zelensky has made ending the war in Donbas his priority, but there has been no major breakthrough in negotiations.
And where are the spectators? Doha can't be London
At the same time, however, the pilgrimage to Doha is a step backwards, as athletics voluntarily and knowingly renounced the thrilling atmosphere that prevailed in the sold-out stadium at London 2017 and at last year's European Championships in Berlin.
Giant banners on the walls of Doha's skyscrapers invite to "the biggest sporting event of 2019". However, concerns are growing about how dignified its backdrop will be.
"Tickets for the finish are sold out on all nights," say organisers.
Only that's too little.
The upper gallery of the Khalifa stadium, with a total capacity of 40,000 spectators, is already covered with colourful tarpaulins, which also display the flags of the 209 participating countries. Athletics has ventured into territory in Qatar where it has no roots despite the annual Diamond League meeting.
No wonder, then, that only 50,000 tickets were sold in total for the ten days of the championships last week, even though their price started at 60 Qatari rials, or less than 400 crowns.
The organisers have now set themselves the target of filling the uncovered parts of the stands at least half full. That is why, according to sources in the British newspaper Giuardian, they are reportedly (although the organisers themselves deny it) giving away free tickets to migrant workers and children. Sebastian Coe, the head of the IAAF Athletics Association, can comment positively: "This is how we can inspire the next generation."
Wealthy Qatar has won world championships in handball and cycling in the past, and after athletics comes football in 2022. The oil superpower's financial bids will always be lucrative even for wealthy sports federations. This is the reality of today's sporting world.
But even if we accept it, and ignore the absence of fans in the stadium, we cannot help but sigh in a purely sporting way that the experiment with the first outdoor World Athletics Championships in the Arabian Peninsula should have been better timed by IAAF leaders - and for a different year. The extremely late date, forced by the climate, upsets the whole scheme of the pre-Olympic season and thus the preparation for the crucial Olympic season, which would normally start in October for the athletes.
Hopefully Qatar will at least make up for it with technological innovations that promise to make the championships ultra-modern and attractive. Isn't it 37 degrees right now? Already the stadium area is artificially air-conditioned to twenty-four. And advanced cameras, built right into the blocks, are meant to give even TV viewers a close-up view of what is happening in the athletes' minds in the hundredths of a second before and just after the starter's shot.
