Overview of bank accounts for children on the Czech market
Banks provide children's accounts free of charge. However, the offer should be considered, as some additional services to the accounts are already charged for. "The motivation for banks to offer accounts for children, whose basic maintenance is usually free, is straightforward. Financial houses are counting on the fact that the waived fees will one day come back to them. With the small migration of Czechs between banks, they are probably not wrong," says Kristýna Kuncová from dTest.
According to her, "small accounts" can do almost everything that adult accounts can. A child gets his or her own payment card, can enter payments, track account movements, and somewhere has his or her own electronic banking. Banks may set up the account, but it's up to parents to teach their children how to use them and also monitor their payments.
"In a relatively flexible way, the parent can set weekly or monthly limits, turn on and off individual services and so on. But above all, they can keep track of what's happening on the account, either by peeking online or through SMS information. Beware, these may no longer be free," Kuncová adds: "If a parent is considering an account for their child, they should consider their child's abilities and capabilities."
The Museum in Semily returns to the Velvet Revolution with an exhibition
An imitation of a normalisation room with a television showing footage of the brutal police crackdown on students in Prague on 17 November 1989. This is also the subject of a new exhibition at the museum in Semily, which is dedicated to the Velvet Revolution. "The basic idea is to present what happened in Semily after the events on Národní třída," said Tomáš Chvátal, the exhibition's curator.
"I would say that the atmosphere was basically the same everywhere, with the exception that the first demonstration in Semily was on 22 November, and then more people gradually packed in every day," he said. Among the most active at the beginning were a group of local dissidents around Miroslav Matěcha, who was the only one from the town and its immediate surroundings to sign Charter 77, and the Dědečks, who circulated a petition called "Several Sentences". According to Chvátal, the Civic Forum was formed relatively quickly. "One specific thing is that there was a very strong group of local doctors in the Civic Forum," the curator said.
Visitors should be drawn into what was happening in the town at the time by some 50 photographs taken 30 years ago by Karel Bárta. A video of the general strike on 27 November 1989, filmed by František Tomíček, has also survived and will be on loop throughout the exhibition. Ivan Hlas also spoke and sang at the demonstration. The Semily archive has also lent a number of preserved banners from that time for the exhibition. "On them were: Let's not get drunk on corn, From trough to trough, We don't want violence," Chvátal said. Some of the changes in the town were very rapid at the time, for example, in December the people voted in an all-Semily vote to make the square Riegrova Square and abolish the previous name Gottwaldovo.
The exhibition also depicts the events before the November events. "In the first part we present to the memorialists and students what was before, a kind of late normalisation. I think we have managed to collect unique documents from Semily, whether they are banners with various communist slogans or a bronze plaque from the then Museum of the Workers' Movement," Chvátal said. One room is meant to evoke a sense of what it might have been like in the living room of an ordinary household back then.
The last part of the exhibition is again dedicated to what was after the Velvet Revolution. It focuses on the first free elections. "We wallpapered one room with election posters. Those who lived through it will remember the posters of With Us to Europe or Václav Klaus still there under the OF banner with the beautiful motto Everyone for his village," the curator added.
A pike in a pond or a relatively prosperous open-air museum?
Babiš chose for his optimistic view statistics such as good security (the Czech Republic is seventh in the world), low unemployment, low national debt. Or the fact that our country is, according to a recent study, twenty-fourth in quality of life out of 140 countries evaluated.
However, developer Dušan Kunovský and architect Josef Pleskot, in a television interview on the occasion of the Architecture and Development Summit, also cited other, not so "rosy" data. For example, that the Czech Republic ranks 154th in the world in the speed of construction procedures. It may be that the current economic "boom" will not leave behind any significant construction legacy as it did in the past.
The biggest obstacle is not only the existing legislation, but also a slow, inefficient bureaucracy. This is also documented by comparative studies, in which the Czech Republic lags significantly behind developed countries in the overall quality and efficiency of public administration.
Our country has simply not yet managed to make good use of the potential of the good economic situation of recent years to invest in the future. While it is nice that salaries and pensions are rising, people with an improving standard of living will also want to have a place to live, modern and fast travel, quality cultural venues, and to live without unbearable environmental burdens.
But in the capital city of Prague, for example, it has been impossible for years to complete the inner and outer ring road or to build a rapid transit or metro to the airport. And Prague does not even have a modern, architecturally daring national library, concert hall or national gallery. The reason for this is not only the absurd tug-of-war over architectural competitions, zoning plans and building permits, but also a kind of specifically Czech conservatism that adheres to the slogan "every bolder change is for the worse".
And when it seems that something bolder might be possible, it is almost certainly thwarted by the conservationists or other somewhat conceited associations or politicians. In the absurd drama surrounding Jan Kaplický's "blob" designed for the new National Library building, even President Václav Klaus wanted to tie himself to the diggers.
But the list does not end with Prague. The Czech Republic is unable to complete its motorway network or start building high-speed trains, so Germany finally decided to run its superfast trains from Berlin to Vienna via a "detour" through Bavaria. Moreover, repairs to existing infrastructure are often drowned in shenanigans. Getting from Prague to Brno quickly is now a conundrum.
Babiš came into politics promising to "make things work". But in terms of meaningful investment and speeding up cumbersome bureaucratic procedures, not much has happened. An amendment to the law on accelerating the construction of transport infrastructure has been in force since 2018, but we will have to wait for more extensive positive effects of, for example, easier land expropriation. And the new construction law, approved by the government, which is said to reduce the current average length of construction proceedings from 5.4 years to one year, will, if we are lucky, start to apply from 2021. But many people would probably not bet on it.
