Protests in Buhari: Pigs' ears thrown by protesters at the government building
Demonstrators against Bulgarian Prime Minister Boyko Borisov and his cabinet threw pig ears at the government building.
This was the latest in a series of protests against "mafia-style governance" that have been taking place in Sofia and other cities for almost three weeks.
Organisers are planning a nationwide blockade for Wednesday, DPA news agency reported.
Today's protest, the 18th in a row, had a weaker turnout than previous ones, according to Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty.
About 300 people had gathered by 20:00 and some streets had to be closed to traffic.
Demonstrators staged a theatrical skit in front of the government building, symbolically locking Prime Minister Borissov and Prosecutor General Ivan Geshev in a prison cell in connection with the arrest of two advisers to President Rumen Radev, a strong political opponent of the prime minister.
The resignation of both is one of the protesters' main demands.
They also demanded the cancellation of the announced health care reform and an end to corruption in construction on the Black Sea coast.
Protest organiser Nikolai Hadzhigenov said on public radio today that the "peak of escalation" was planned for Wednesday in the form of "a national rally in Sofia and blockades across the country".
He reiterated the demand for the resignation of Borissov and his government, as well as for early elections.
Ordinary ones should be held in March 2021.
Borisov has previously said that he does not intend to resign.
He justified this, among other things, by the need to guide Bulgaria through the covid-19 pandemic and the resulting economic crisis.
But on Friday he replaced five members of his government team, although the concession did not appease the demonstrators.
Earlier this week, Borisov's government survived a confidence vote in parliament.
Supreme prosecutor reinstates prosecution of mother who manipulated daughter against father
Supreme State Prosecutor Pavel Zeman disagrees with the acquittal of a mother who manipulated her daughter and damaged her relationship with her father over a long period of time. She faced charges of abuse and endangering her upbringing. The regional court acquitted her, but Zeman disagrees. His appeal to the Supreme Court suggests that such conduct may constitute a criminal offence.
The Supreme Court's decision could have wider implications for other cases. "A more specific definition of such a specific form of abuse can be considered necessary also in terms of guiding further application practice," Zeman's appeal states.
Last year, the district court in Svitavy initially found the woman guilty of both abuse of a ward and endangering the upbringing of a child. She had formed a strong, almost symbiotic bond with her daughter, even when she was supposed to be entrusted to her father.
The result was a pathological fixation on the mother and a markedly negative relationship with the father. The situation marked the emotional development of the daughter, who was even hospitalised. She had threatened to harm herself if she was handed over to her father's care.
The Svitavy court sentenced the mother to two years' imprisonment with a two-year suspended sentence. However, the Pardubice branch of the regional court acquitted the woman on appeal, saying it was not a criminal offence. The regional court repeated the same verdict after the Supreme Court ordered it to decide again.
The Regional Court stated that situations where one parent manipulates a child against the other are by no means exceptional. They are dealt with in custody proceedings, possibly with the help of psychologists or youth welfare authorities. Only rarely is criminal law the solution.
However, according to the Attorney General, the woman had committed both abuse and endangering the child's upbringing. "The accused acted quite purposely in arousing negative feelings in her daughter towards her father, and purposely reinforced those negative emotions. In doing so, she not only pursued the unlawful intention to restrict or exclude the father's contact with the minor, but she must necessarily have been aware that this would have negative consequences in the minor's psychosocial sphere," the appeal states.
Zeman asked the Supreme Court to send the case back to the regional court once more. The appeal states that the child is now in the custody of the father.
