Milan Jakubů: The army stole the funeral for themselves! Says Andor Šándor
There is still confusion around the funeral of Brigadier General Milan Jakubů. Media speculated during the week that the army planned the last farewell to the deputy director of Military Intelligence as bombastic as soldiers can, despite the wishes of the family. There were also discrepancies over the date of the funeral. Defence Ministry spokesman Jan Pejšek denied this.
"It's nonsense! We have been in contact with the family from the beginning, the Friday date of the funeral has been agreed from the beginning, nobody has changed it. The same applies to the military honours. We are still discussing the possible participation of the media with regard to the family," Pejšek told Blesk on Wednesday. The funeral will finally take place on Friday and will not lack all the military honours, including a flyover by fighter jets.
But there is still a tense atmosphere around the final farewell to the popular general. The organizers have decided not to have people who worked with the general in the past attend the funeral ceremony!
This includes, for example, the former head of military intelligence Andor Šándor (62), who met Milan Jakubů 17 years ago. Šándor remembers his former colleague as hard-working, intelligent and a "good guy".
In addition, in recent years he regularly met him at the anniversary celebrations of the founding of the Military Intelligence. That is why he would like to say goodbye to Milan Jakubů. "I would personally go to Milan Jakubů's funeral," Šándor told Blesk. But he can't.
"I know of other people from the organization who would like to go, but they are unlucky because the potentates are usurping the funeral for themselves. I think it is not right to privatize a funeral in this way," the security expert said. He is also not happy with the alleged consideration of closing the ceremony to the public due to the secrecy of the army top brass.
"The leadership of the army is not classified and neither are the leaders of military intelligence, because they are promoted at Prague Castle, for example, we see them there. If the media information is true and the family has indeed been overlooked by the military, it is of course a family matter. I personally would never allow the army to overrule the family and its wishes," Šándor concluded.
