There is no threat to the launch of the new toll, reports Kremlik. But a change of operator is at stake
The Transport Ministry on Friday started preparations for a new tender for the operation of the new toll system. This is a backup plan that the state would use in case the current toll contract is finally cancelled. In addition, the state is also preparing another interim solution in case the tender cannot be completed on time. Transport Minister Vladimír Kremlík (ANO) said this on Facebook.
On Thursday, the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS) banned the performance of the toll contract between the state and the CzechToll/SkyToll consortium, with a one-year delay. The ministry will file an appeal against the decision.
"The launch of the new toll collection system is not at risk. Starting today, we are launching the preparation of a new transparent tender procedure, the subject of which will be the services for the operation of the new toll system, which is currently being completed by the consortium of CzechToll and SkyToll," the minister said.
The state would thus be looking for the operator of the toll system currently under preparation, which will be launched in December this year. It would therefore not be a competition for a completely new toll system, as was the case in the last tender, nor would it involve the use of the old system currently operated by Kapsch.
However, according to Kremlik, the ministry is also preparing for the fact that it would not be able to prepare the new tender in time. "Based on my experience with the toll tender process so far, I am deeply convinced that the Office is wrong and that it is objectively impossible to prepare and implement such a complex tender procedure and hand over the operation of the toll system to a new operator within the 12-month period set by the Office," he said.
The ministry will therefore prepare an interim solution in addition to a new tender procedure, which would solve the collection of tolls for a transitional period until the state finds a full-fledged solution.
Thus, the state will probably not yet use the offer submitted to it in recent days by the current toll administrator Kapsch. The Austrian firm offered to operate the current system for the state in case the toll contract is cancelled.
At the same time, Kremlik reiterated his belief that a back-up plan would not be needed. The ministry will therefore file an appeal against the decision of the antitrust authority.
On Thursday, the Office issued a decision banning the implementation of the toll contract. However, the ban will not take effect until a year after the authority's decision becomes final. It is not final and can be appealed to the president of the office. The ministry and CzechToll are therefore continuing to prepare the new toll, which is expected to be launched in December.
Last year, the CzechToll/SkyToll consortium won the tender for the new toll system and its operator. It won the toll tender with a bid of CZK 10.75 billion for a ten-year operation. The current operator, Kapsch, protested against the tender process and the validity of the toll contract, as it failed in the tender with a bid of over CZK 13 billion.
