A pedestrian was walking on it at the time and immediately called the police.
Upon arrival at the address in the western part of the city, the patrol noticed an open window with the chair still lying underneath and several cans and cigarette butts next to it.
"The noise coming from the fourth floor room indicated that a rather noisy party was going on inside.
Officers walked down the corridor to the apartment and asked the three young men present, aged between twenty-six and twenty-nine, for an explanation," said officers' spokesman Jacob Ghanem.
The young Czechs think they are good with money. The survey did not confirm this
"So it turns out that young Czechs are somewhat more confident in their knowledge of finances than is the reality. A significantly higher proportion of wrong answers were given by women and respondents without a high school diploma," said KRUK director Jaroslava Palendalová.
Men and young high school or university graduates are more likely to trust their knowledge about financial products.
Young Czechs learn the most about the workings of financial matters from their parents (37 percent), through self-study on the internet (23 percent) and only in third place from lessons at school (21 percent).
It is mainly women who consult their parents about financial matters, while men are more likely to look for information on the internet. Getting information about finances from parents is prevalent among young people of all ages, regardless of their educational attainment or personal income. Brochures from financial institutions, professional magazines and publications have practically minimal influence.
"Once again, the importance of children being brought up by their parents, who are the authority in all major areas of life, becomes apparent. Therefore, the level of financial literacy of parents, who pass on their knowledge and experience to their offspring, is crucial," Palendalova said.
Savings and investments are preferred by 94 per cent of young people.
Young people are unanimous on the question of whether it is better to save and buy, for example, their own house or apartment, or to enjoy and spend money rather than save and own a home.
The strategy of saving and investing in fixed assets is shared by 94 per cent of respondents. This is true across all age categories of young people, regardless of educational attainment, social status or current level of personal income.
The survey strategy is then 100 per cent held by married people with two or more children and public sector employees. On the other hand, people living alone and with an income above CZK 30,000 per month are more likely to want to enjoy themselves.
