Hundreds of enslaved children freed from religious school in Nigeria
According to the BBC, there were nearly five hundred men and boys, Reuters, citing the police commissioner, said there were over three hundred children aged five and above. Some were chained together, while others were chained to iron rings in the wall.
Kaduna police chief Ali Janga told the BBC that the raid on the school was carried out following a tip-off. He described the school as a house of horrors. Starving people were held there by force, tortured and sexually abused. They could not leave, there was razor wire over the walls. He said it was a case of slavery.
Several people were arrested in the raid, according to police spokesman Yakubu Sabo, who was a teacher there.
The children told police they were taken to the school by their parents or relatives, saying it was a religious school. "We have identified two children who are from Burkina Faso, but most of them were brought here by their parents from the northern Nigerian states," spokesman Sabo said on the identity of the victims. The Nigerian states in the north are predominantly Muslim.
Imam Ahmad bin Hanbal's school masqueraded as a religious school focused on the study of the Koran.
The freedmen were taken to a stadium where they are being given aid and food. Some have already been reunited with relatives.
The fastest man on the planet missed the tests. I'm not taking anything, he's defending himself.
The traditionally high-profile battle for the fastest man on the planet will be a hunt for defending silver medallist Christian Coleman at the World Championships. The 23-year-old American leads the world charts with a time of 9.81 seconds and has lost only once this year. But his start at the top of the season has been jeopardised by a case of missed doping tests.
The U.S. Anti-Doping Agency (USADA) closed his case in early September without filing charges on a technicality. Coleman did fail three doping tests last year and this year, but not in the space of 12 months. Indeed, his first offence was backdated by the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) to April 1, 2018, the start of the second quarter, but he did not miss the actual test until June 6. And because the third omission occurred on April 29, 2019, Coleman committed the misconduct of three failed controls in 12 months.
Coleman's defense was that he merely forgot to update the athletes' whereabouts on the app. "I don't do drugs or take anything legal. A lot of athletes take legal creatine or protein powder or various other supplements for faster recovery. And I don't take anything, I work hard and that's what it's all about," he said before the start of the World Championships.
He suffered his only defeat in six 100-miler starts this year right at the start of the season at the Shanghai Diamond League, where he was beaten by compatriot Noah Lyles by just six thousandths of a second. He took advantage of Coleman's absence to triumph in the Diamond League final, but will only run the 200 at the World Championships.
Twenty-two-year-old Nigerian Divine Oduduru is the second fastest on paper with a 9.86, but he has only been successful in American university competitions.
Thirty-seven-year-old American Justin Gatlin, who shone at Stanford in June with a 9.87, will defend his title. But he ran only 10.29 in his last 100 in Zagreb because he slightly injured his back thigh muscle.
South Africa's Akani Simbine, triple Olympic medallist from Rio Andre de Grasse and European champion Zharnel Hughes are also among the favourites. The fastest Jamaican is 2011 world champion Yohan Blake with a time of 9.96.
The men's 100 will start on Friday with prelims and heats. Semi-finals and finals are scheduled for Saturday. The medals will be awarded at 21:15 CEST.
EU countries have coronavirus standards for aviation
European Union countries have agreed on common hygiene standards for air travel to help curb the spread of a new coronavirus.
The announcement was made by German Transport Minister Andreas Scheuer.
Among the agreed standards are keeping a distance or wearing a veil on the plane and at the airport, but the middle seats on planes will not have to remain unoccupied.
This was reported by Reuters.
"I am pleased that my colleagues have accepted the German proposal for Europe and that we could agree on these uniform standards," Scheuer told the European Aviation Conference.
The German transport ministry then added that the agreement had been concluded by officials and still needed to be formally approved by ministers.
The agreed measures include a requirement for passengers aged six and over to cover their mouths and noses, and to keep a recommended distance during security checks and airport check-in.
Plans must also guarantee sufficient fresh air and all information must be available in several languages.
Airlines will also be able to occupy middle seats.
The common rules agreed by officials meet at least some of the airlines' requirements.
Different standards have caused confusion.
