Soldiers rehearse, draw the curtains. China plans celebrations at the site of the massacre
The army rehearsed the parade over recent weekends. Shops in downtown Beijing had to close and residents near the square were ordered to draw curtains. Military vehicles rolled down the empty streets to the square and warplanes circled in the sky.
Several Chinese told Reuters they were proud that their country was putting its military might on display. But one woman said it was hard to deny that the celebrations would make other countries uneasy.
She was apparently referring to Taiwan, which China claims and where elections are coming up. But there may also be concerns in the semi-autonomous city of Hong Kong, where thousands of people have repeatedly demonstrated against the Chinese-installed administrator.
Celebrations are also afoot outside Beijing. The southern Chinese port of Xiamen has already put on a special light show on Thursday night. Sia-men lies across from island Taiwan and is one of China's top ten most innovative cities.
Ahead of the anniversary, the list of banned items is growing. It already includes drones, balloons, kites, alcohol, walkie-talkies and devices that use radio waves, the Guardian pointed out. China's popular social network Weibo is deleting "harmful political information", it added.
"It's another milestone, another opportunity to show that the Chinese Communist Party remains (at the helm) despite all the predictions," said Maura Cunningham, a historian who studies China. "It's a moment when the party can demonstrate order, control and power," she added.
The People's Republic of China was formed in 1949 when the Communists, led by Mao Zedong, won their battle with Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists, who retreated to Taiwan.
In the second half of the 1960s, China underwent a disastrous communist experiment in the form of the so-called Cultural Revolution. In June 1989, the regime massacred thousands of pro-democracy demonstrators, both students and workers, in Tiananmen Square with tanks.
Since the late 1970s, China has increasingly adopted elements of a capitalist economy. Critics say it is now a mixture of the worst of communism (one party monopoly and persecution of the opposition) and (Dickensian) capitalism (exploitation of workers).
