Trump considers canceling registration of Chinese stocks in the U.S.
US President Donald Trump's administration is considering revoking permission for Chinese firms to trade on US stock markets. An informed source told Reuters today. Such a move would be a radical escalation of trade tensions between the US and China. Shares of the affected companies on the New York Stock Exchange immediately headed down after the news, taking the entire market down with them.
The stock withdrawal would be part of a broader effort to curb U.S. investment in China, the source added. It confirmed a Bloomberg report that had sent shockwaves through financial markets shortly before. Shares of Chinese firms Alibaba Group Holding, JD.com, Pinduoduo, Baidu, Vipshop Holdings, Baozun and IQIYI lost between two and four percent.
Shares of 156 Chinese companies are traded on the Nasdaq and NYSE exchanges in the US, according to government data from February. They include at least 11 state-owned enterprises.
Bloomberg pointed out that the exact mechanism to withdraw Chinese companies' shares from the US exchanges has not yet been worked out. A possible plan would have to be approved by Trump, who has given the green light to negotiations on the matter.
China and the US have been engaged in a trade war for more than a year, imposing tariffs on each other. The dispute between the two countries is having a negative impact on the world economy and has raised fears of a global economic recession. Washington is using tariffs to try to get Beijing to change its trade practices and reduce China's trade surplus with the US.
According to CNBC television, trade talks between the US and China are expected to resume on October 10. Its goal is to end the trade war.
Former French President Chirac to be buried on Monday, public memorial service on Sunday
The funeral of former French President Jacques Chirac, who died on Thursday at the age of 86, will take place on Monday evening at the Montparnasse cemetery in Paris. French media reports citing Chirac's family. The ceremony will be private.
The public will be able to bid farewell to the former head of state on Sunday afternoon at a memorial service at the Invalides in Paris, where Chirac's coffin containing his remains will be displayed, the Elysee Palace announced.
Crowds have been streaming into the presidential residence since Thursday evening to sign the book of condolences, according to AFP. This will be possible until Sunday. Then on Monday, President Emmanuel Macron declared a state of mourning.
Meanwhile, more reactions are pouring in from around the world and from France to the death of the former mayor of Paris and president from 1995 to 2007, whom Prime Minister Édouard Philippe today described as "a Frenchman in the true sense of the word".
Chirac was remembered by the Japanese, for example, as the politician was known for his love of his country and the sport of sumo. The news of the former French President's death has appeared on the front pages of all the Japanese newspapers, including the sporting ones, the French press notes.
The museum of tribal art on Paris' Quai Branly, which Chirac founded, will not charge admission for ten days in honour of the former head of state.
Arctic Svalbard hits temperature record of almost 22 degrees
"A 41-year-old record has fallen in Longyearbyen," the Norwegian Meteorological Institute said on Twitter.
The temperature there rose to 21.7 degrees Celsius in the afternoon, breaking the 1979 record by 0.4 degrees, it added.
The roughly 2,000-strong Longyearbyen is the largest town in Svalbard, located about 1,300 kilometres from the North Pole.
Svalbard is warming faster than almost any other place on Earth.
This fact highlights the dangers of warming elsewhere in the Arctic - from Alaska to Siberia, according to a report last year by the Norwegian Centre for Climate Studies.
The average temperature in Svalbard has risen by three to five degrees since the 1970s, it said.
By 2100, it could rise by as much as ten degrees if greenhouse gas emissions into the atmosphere are not reduced.
Rising temperatures in Svalbard may result in the thawing of permafrost, which will threaten the stability of many buildings, roads and airports, and may cause more avalanches and landslides.
Climate warming also threatens Arctic fauna such as polar bears and seals, which depend on the ocean's ice cover.
