No Czechs or children allowed. The CTIA has detected discrimination in restaurants
These included misinformation on prices and failure to comply with the principles of fairness in sales.
In one case of discrimination, a restaurant in Prague refused to allow smaller children into the establishment. According to the CTIA, its website states that the establishment is not suitable for children under the age of eight. "When asked electronically by a consumer whether it was possible to order a table for four adults and one child aged four at that restaurant, an employee of the restaurant replied electronically that they do not accept the presence of children under eight," Fröhlich added.
In the second case, another Prague establishment refused to allow Czech speakers to sit at the table, while allowing English speakers to do so. "The Czech-speaking inspectors, in their capacity as consumers, were not allowed to sit down at the restaurant and place an order. English-speaking consumers were allowed to do so," a spokesman for the CTIA described the situation.
