The Brno Grand Prix? Ticket prices threatened
The most expensive item before the Grand Prix every year is the entry fee. This year it was about one hundred and fifteen million crowns. "The mass of people who come to Brno during the Grand Prix spend money on accommodation, food and entertainment, which should more or less balance the costs associated with the event, including the entry fee," said Petr Pelc, an economist.
According to him, the importance of the race is also in attracting tourists to the city. "Brno does not have that many world-class tourist attractions. The Grand Prix attracts visitors from abroad. It is as important for Brno as, for example, the Turin airport or the exhibition centre. And these are projects that are supported by public money," the economist added.
The Grand Prix in Brno
- Cost over the past five years: CZK 686 million
- profits from the past five editions: 682 million crowns
- problem: lack of money for the organisation, increasing registration fee for the Dorna promotion company
- possible solutions: more money from the state, use of advertising space, increase in ticket prices
- current status: negotiations on a new contract for the next five years
According to Filip Hrůza, director of the Institute of Public Administration, the organisers must now evaluate whether the race is profitable for Brno. "The Grand Prix siphons money from public budgets for other matters. To some extent, however, this is a political question, not an economic one," he said.
In the future, the costs of the motoring event could be even higher. The option of almost doubling the registration fee is in play.
"The situation is not closed, we have to try to negotiate the best possible conditions with Dorna. It also depends on the extent to which the state is prepared to contribute to the organisation of the race. If the worst scenarios come true, I am afraid it is not realistic for the city and the region to pay the amount," admitted Brno Mayor Markéta Vaňková.
As Deník Rovnost has already reported, representatives of the South Moravian Region and Brno are also discussing the possibility of using advertising because of the difficulties in raising money for the Grand Prix. "Dorna's condition is that advertising must be placed in places that are not occupied by cameras. The choice of companies is also limited, because if Dorna has a general sponsor, the second sponsor cannot be a company from the same area," Vaňková explained.
The organisers can also raise more money from tickets in the coming years. "We have to sit down and say what the costs will actually be. And we have to adjust the re-pricing of tickets to that," said Brno's opposition ANO deputy and former mayor Petr Vokřál.
