Nečesaný wants 45 million from the state
According to spokesman Vladimír Řepka, the Justice Ministry has received six requests in this regard and is now analysing them. The young man was in prison for two years for assaulting the woman, but the judiciary eventually acquitted him.
Neither the Supreme State Prosecutor Pavel Zeman nor Justice Minister Marie Benešová filed an appeal in the case.
The attempted murder of the hairdresser in Hořice happened in February 2013. The Hradec state prosecutor's office accused Nečesaný, a 20-year-old student at a grammar school at the time, of the crime. The prosecution claimed that he hit the woman several times on the head with a log and then took over ten thousand crowns from her. The woman was found seriously injured by her son and her life was saved by doctors at a hospital in Hradec Králové.
Nečesaný denied any guilt from the beginning. "I am innocent and I swear it. I am sincerely sorry for what happened to the victim, but I am not the perpetrator," the young man, who did not deny having been in the hairdresser's on the fateful day, said in court earlier. He said he wanted to get a haircut. However, he left after the woman told him that she was closing. He then turned himself in to the police as a witness.
The hairdresser did not recognize him as the aggressor when she questioned him, but later identified Nečesaný as the attacker. According to forensic experts, she suffered memory lapses after the attack.
The Hradec Králové Regional Court handed down five verdicts in the case. First, it found Nečesaný guilty twice and sentenced him to 16 years in prison; the Supreme Court of Appeal reduced his sentence to 13 years. Nečesaný went behind bars twice, but each time he was released after the Supreme Court intervened. After a change of the trial chamber was ordered, repeated acquittals were eventually handed down, the last of which was upheld by the Supreme Court in March this year.
At the same time, however, the president of the appeals chamber, Jiří Lněnička, said in his reasoning that the decision was wrong, but said he had no better option given the procedural situation. He said he dismissed the prosecutor's appeal against the acquittal verdict even though her appeal objections were legitimate.
"The problem with this case is not that there is a lack of evidence, but the evaluation of the evidence. We consider that sufficient evidence was gathered in the preliminary proceedings, which in another criminal case would have been abundantly sufficient for a guilty verdict," Lněnička said.
However, both the Hradec Králové and Supreme Courts viewed the case differently and their opinion would probably not be changed by further reversal of the acquittal.
