The lessee shall be entitled to interest on the security deposit from the time it is provided at the legal rate.
V. Rights and obligations of the parties
The Lessor undertakes to:
- to transfer the subject of the lease to the lessee so that he/she may use it for the agreed purpose, to maintain the apartment and the house in a fit state for use during the lease period and to keep the house in the proper order customary in the local conditions during the lease period
- remedy the damage or defect within a reasonable time after the tenant has notified the tenant of the damage or defect.
If the landlord fails to remedy the damage or defect without undue delay and in a proper manner, the tenant may remedy the damage or defect and claim reimbursement of reasonable costs or a reduction in rent, unless the damage or defect is not substantial.
If the tenant fails to notify the landlord of the damage or defect without undue delay after he should and could with due diligence have discovered it, he shall not be entitled to reimbursement of costs; if he removes the damage or defect himself, he shall not be entitled to a reduction in the rent.
- to ensure the undisturbed use of the leased premises by the tenant for the duration of the lease
- to carry out other maintenance of the subject of the lease and necessary repairs thereof which the lessee is not obliged to carry out
Tenant's rights:
- if it does not cause an increased burden on the apartment or the house, the tenant may work or run a business in the apartment
- keep an animal in the flat if the keeping of the animal does not cause the landlord or the other occupants of the house a nuisance disproportionate to the conditions in the house.
If the breeding causes the need for increased costs for the maintenance of the common parts of the house, the tenant is obliged to reimburse the landlord for these costs.
- to carry out, with the landlord's consent, alterations, remodelling or other changes to the flat or house.
If the landlord does not consent to a modification that is necessary because of a disability of the tenant, a member of the tenant's household or another person living in the apartment, without having a serious and just reason for refusing consent, the court shall substitute the landlord's consent at the tenant's request.
At the termination of the tenancy, the tenant shall remove the alteration he has made in the apartment or house, unless the landlord does not request restoration to the previous state.
- to accept anyone in his or her home.
If the tenant takes in a new member of his household, he shall notify the landlord without undue delay of the increase in the number of persons living in the flat; if the tenant fails to do so even within two months of the change, he shall be deemed to have seriously breached his obligation.
The landlord shall have the right to require that only such number of persons shall live in the tenant's household as is reasonable for the size of the apartment and does not prevent all of them from living in the apartment in customary comfortable and hygienic conditions.
If the number of members of the tenant's household decreases, the tenant shall notify the landlord without undue delay.
Tenant's obligations:
- to use the apartment properly in accordance with the lease agreement
- to observe during the tenancy the rules of conduct customary in the house and the landlord's reasonable instructions for the maintenance of good order customary in the local circumstances
- carry out and pay for routine maintenance and minor repairs related to the use of the apartment
- to tolerate alterations to the flat or house, or its reconstruction or other change, only if they do not diminish the value of the dwelling and can be carried out without major inconvenience to the tenant, or if the landlord carries them out on the order of a public authority, or if there is a direct threat of particularly serious harm.
In other cases, the change may be made only with the consent of the tenant.
- If the tenant discovers damage or defect in the apartment which must be remedied without delay, he shall immediately notify the landlord; any other defect or damage which prevents normal living shall be notified to the landlord without undue delay.
The tenant shall do all that he can reasonably be expected to do to ensure that the damage or defect to be remedied without delay does not cause further damage.
The lessee is entitled to compensation for the costs reasonably incurred in preventing further damage, unless the damage or defect was caused by circumstances for which the lessee is liable.
- If the tenant knows in advance that he will be absent from the apartment for more than two months and that the apartment will be difficult to access for that period, he must notify the landlord in good time.
At the same time, he shall notify the person who will ensure that he is able to enter the apartment during his absence in the event that this is strictly necessary; if the tenant does not have such a person at hand, the landlord shall be that person.
If the tenant fails to comply with this obligation, this shall be deemed to be a breach of the tenant's obligations in a serious manner; this shall not apply unless serious damage occurs as a result.
- to pay the rent under this agreement
- to carry out routine maintenance of the subject of the lease
- to notify the lessor that the property has a defect which the lessor is obliged to remedy immediately after he has discovered it or could have discovered it by careful use of the property
- if a third party claims ownership or other rights in the thing, or if a third party demands delivery or eviction of the thing, the tenant shall notify the landlord in writing; if the tenant so requests, the landlord shall provide protection.
If the landlord fails to provide the tenant with sufficient protection, the tenant may terminate the lease without notice.
