VI. Subletting
The tenant may sublet part of the flat to a third party only if he himself lives in the flat.
Section 2272 of the Civil Code shall apply mutatis mutandis.
If the tenant does not permanently reside in the apartment himself, he may sublet the apartment or a part thereof to a third party only with the written consent of the landlord.
The request for consent must also be in writing.
If the landlord does not respond to the request within one month, the consent is deemed to have been given.
If the tenant violates the obligations agreed upon above, he shall be deemed to have grossly breached his obligation.
The sublease shall end together with the tenancy.
If the tenancy ends, the tenant must notify the subtenant in good time, stating the relevant facts, which are in particular the date of termination of the tenancy, the length of the notice period and the start of the notice period.
If the subtenant allows a third party to use the property in accordance with the law and this agreement, the subtenant shall be liable to the landlord for the actions of that person in the same way as if he had used the property himself.
VII. Termination of the lease
Upon surrender of the thing, the lessee shall be entitled to separate and take away everything he has put into or on the thing at his own expense, if this is possible and if this does not impair the substance of the thing or make its use unreasonably difficult.
If the dwelling becomes dilapidated during the term of the lease, the lease shall terminate.
If the apartment is partly destroyed during the term of the lease, the tenant is entitled either to a reasonable reduction in the rent or to terminate the lease without notice.
Notice of termination of the lease must be in writing and must be given to the other party.
The period of notice shall run from the first day of the calendar month following the date on which the notice is received by the other party.
In the event of termination by the landlord, the landlord is obliged to inform the tenant of his right to object to the termination and to request a court review of the validity of the termination.
The landlord may terminate the lease within the three-month notice period only for the reasons set out in Section 2288 of the Civil Code, and is obliged to state the reason for termination in the notice.
The tenant has the right to petition the court to review whether the termination is justified within two months from the date of receipt of the notice.
The landlord has the right to terminate the lease without notice in accordance with Section 2291 of the Civil Code.
