a. if the tenant has not paid the rent and utility costs for at least three months,
b. if he or she damages the apartment or the house in a serious or irreparable way,
c. if he or she otherwise causes serious damage or inconvenience to the landlord or to the persons living in the house or
d. if he or she unlawfully uses the flat in a manner or for a purpose other than that agreed.
If the landlord does not specify in the notice what he considers to be a particularly serious breach of the tenant's duty or if he does not, before serving the notice, require the tenant to remedy his defective behaviour or to remedy the unlawful condition within a reasonable time, the notice shall not be taken into account.
The tenant shall be obliged to surrender the apartment to the landlord on the day on which the tenancy ends.
The apartment is surrendered if the landlord receives the keys and is not otherwise prevented from accessing and using the apartment.
If the tenant leaves the apartment in such a way that the tenancy can be deemed to have ended without any doubt, the apartment shall be deemed to have been surrendered immediately.
The tenant shall be obliged to hand over the apartment in the condition in which he took it over, notwithstanding normal wear and tear of ordinary use and defects which the landlord is obliged to remedy.
The tenant is obliged to remove any changes made to the apartment with the landlord's consent, provided that the parties have agreed that the tenant will restore the apartment to its original condition at the end of the lease.
The tenant is obliged to remove the alterations made to the flat without the landlord's consent, unless the landlord informs the tenant that he does not require the removal of the alterations; the tenant may not nevertheless claim compensation even if the alterations have increased the value of the flat.
The landlord may claim compensation in the amount of the decrease in the value of the apartment caused by the changes made by the tenant without the landlord's consent.
Fixtures and fittings fixed in the walls, floor and ceiling of the flat which cannot be removed without unreasonable diminution in value or without damage to the flat or the house shall pass by fixing or insertion to the owner of the flat.
The tenant shall have the right to demand that the landlord deal with him without undue delay; this shall not apply to what the tenant has done without the landlord's consent.
The settlement is due no later than the date of termination of the tenancy.
The landlord shall be entitled to compensation in the amount of the agreed rent if the tenant fails to hand over the apartment to the landlord on the day of termination of the tenancy until the day on which the tenant actually hands over the apartment to the landlord.
If an item remains in the flat which may be deemed to belong to the tenant or a member of his household, the landlord shall take care of the item for the benefit of the tenant and on his account.
If the tenant does not take possession of the item without undue delay, the landlord shall have the right to sell the item in a suitable manner at the tenant's expense after giving the tenant a reasonable additional period of time to take possession.
This shall not apply if the item is one which the tenant or a member of his household has apparently abandoned.
The tenant may terminate the tenancy if the circumstances on which the parties apparently based the obligation under the tenancy agreement have changed to such an extent that the tenant cannot reasonably be required to continue the tenancy.
In the event of the death of the tenant, the contract shall be governed by Sections 2279 et seq. of the Civil Code.
